      "description": "The Bill of Rights (BoR) remains a scaffold with all six articles marked '[To be defined by human principal]'. No operative scope, prohibited activities, core identity, human authority reservations, amendment protocol, or interpretation rules are established. Arbiter (#190) verifies the BoR at every scope query; an empty BoR means the scope gate is effectively undefined, allowing any action to pass the first compliance gate by default. This leaves the DIO operationally unconstrained and violates the constitutional role of the BoR as the supreme governing perimeter.",
      "source": "Bill of Rights, Articles I, II, III, IV, V, VI (all undefined); MSP Section 'Relationship to the Bill of Rights' (which states MSP is subordinate to BoR and any conflict voids the MSP rule)",
      "criticality": "Critical",
      "urgency": "High",
      "impact": "High",
      "reason": "Without a defined BoR, the entire regulatory framework collapses: the scope gate is non-existent, and the MSP has no superior law to subordinate to. Any governance-class event could execute operations without human-defined ethical or legal boundaries, exposing the enterprise to unbounded risk. The MSP's role as a precision translation of the BoR is impossible, rendering Nomos's two-gate adjudication effectively a single-gate system that defaults to permissive evaluation. This gap must be closed before any governance-class events can be meaningfully assessed."
